chunk_metadata.text: ## MAXIMO SELF-PACED TRAINING GUIDE ## HEALTHCARE TECHNOLOGY MANAGEMENT - HTM TECH TRAINING ## HTM Tech Roles in Maximo In Maximo, HTM Techs/Tech Plus roles can review and create related Work Orders to Service Requests, review, assign, take ownership, update statuses and complete Work Orders. The difference between the HTM Tech and HTM Tech Plus role is that the Tech cannot assign Work Orders to another Tech whereas the Tech Plus can. ## Available Training Resources User Guides, Job Aids and Quick Reference Documents are available on the EAWM Maximo Training Page to help users learn their role and responsibilities in Maximo at their own pace and in a mode that best fits their learning style. - · User Guides provide the greatest amount of detail on each topic. User Guides include a high-level summary, detailed step-by-step instructions with screen captures, and a Business Process Model mapping out the activities performed by each affected Functional Community.

r Guides include a high-level summary, detailed step-by-step instructions with screen captures, and a Business Process Model mapping out the activities performed by each affected Functional Community. User Guides can be found in the 'Training Materials by Role' section of the Training page, under via links to the Functional Community and Role name. - · Job Aids target critical functionality in Maximo. These documents are intended to be brief and focus on key issues, highlighting essential steps. These are found in the 'User Documentation' section of the Training page. - · Quick Reference Documents (QRDs) include step-by-step work instructions, in simplest terms. Unlike Job Aids and User Guides, QRDs normally do not include screen captures. These are also posted in the 'User Documentation' section. In addition to the items available on the Training page, this Self-Paced Training Guide directs you to short video demonstrations recorded and narrated by Maximo Instructors as they walk thro

In addition to the items available on the Training page, this Self-Paced Training Guide directs you to short video demonstrations recorded and narrated by Maximo Instructors as they walk through the steps of completing specific tasks in Maximo. To train for your role, read the appropriate User Guide, Job Aid and/or QRD for a given topic to gain an understanding of the process. Also, watch the video demonstrations as noted below. Continue reviewing this information until you are ready to start working in Maximo. IMPORTANT! Please DO NOT attempt to practice any of the steps in the Maximo Production system. If, after reviewing the materials, you are still uncomfortable with working in Maximo, contact your Maximo Site Lead for additional guidance. ## MAXIMO SELF-PACED TRAINING GUIDE ## 1. Request Work HTM Techs can use the Maximo Service Requests application to create a new Service Request and the Work Order Tracking application to create new Work Orders.

Request Work HTM Techs can use the Maximo Service Requests application to create a new Service Request and the Work Order Tracking application to create new Work Orders. In some cases, only the Work Order will be created. Service Requests are used to request work to be done by another Department. - · To read the User Guide on this topic, please go to the HTM Tech Training Materials page; under the HTM Tech tab, select the Request Work User Guide to download the file. - · To see demonstrations of using Maximo, please go to the EAWM Maximo Video Demos. Under the section, Healthcare Technology Management (HTM) , locate the videos for the role HTM Tech/Plus . The following video demonstrations pertain to this topic (please note that the videos will launch in a separate media player): - o Create a Service Request - o Create Related Work Order from Service Request - o Create a New Work Order without a Service Request - o Print Work Order ## 2.

Asset Turn In Work Order Completing an Asset Turn In Work Order is the same as completing any Work Order in Maximo. The key difference is to ensure Sanitization and/or Decontamination of the Asset(s) is completed by the Responsible Tech and depending on your local business process, verified by a Supervisor. If authorized, a Tech can verify sanitization. Key points to remember are that once work is completed, the Work Order must be in the Status of COMPLETE and the associated Service Request in the Status of WSAN (Waiting on Sanitization). These two factors will enable the ISO to be notified, allowi

leted, the Work Order must be in the Status of COMPLETE and the associated Service Request in the Status of WSAN (Waiting on Sanitization). These two factors will enable the ISO to be notified, allowing them to certify the Asset(s) have been sanitized. - · To read the User Guide on this topic, please go to the HTM Tech Training Materials page; under the HTM Tech or the HTM Tech Plus tab, select the Asset Turn In User Guide to download the file.

Service Requests are reviewed by the function receiving them and turned into Work Orders once approved. The Work Orders are then scheduled and assigned to a person and/or shop. For more information about this process, please go to Appendix C - Request Work Business Process to view the flowchart and narrative. ## User Roles and Responsibilities The audience for this training includes the fol

Service Requests can be submitted for yourself or on behalf of another person. Service Requests are reviewed by the function receiving them and turned into Work Orders once approved. You have the option of automatically receiving key status notifications for any Service Request that you create.

A WORK ORDER ## Create a Related Work Order from a Service Request Work Orders can be created automatically from existing Service Requests. This creates a relationship between the two records and the Asset and/or location from the originating Service Request is copied to the related Work Order. There are various ways to create a Work Order, depending on how it originated: - · If the request came in as a Service Request, then you will create the Work Order from the Service Request, which is the case in our scenario. (This will take place the majority of the time.) - · If the request originated as a Work Order, then you will use the Work Order Tracking application. For example: standing work orders, work orders created for professional services. Refer to Appendix A - Creating a Work Order Using Work Order Tracking for the steps on how to do it. - · If the work being reported has been completed before a Work Order was ever created, you will use the Quick Reporting application.

ork Order Using Work Order Tracking for the steps on how to do it. - · If the work being reported has been completed before a Work Order was ever created, you will use the Quick Reporting application. This is a relatively rare scenario; it is generally reserved for work either, found and fixed while away from your desk or for work that couldn't wait for a work order to be created. Refer to Appendix B: - Creating a Work Order Using Quick Reporting for details related to this process. Note that the preferred method to create a Work Order is using Work Order Tracking and not Quick Reporting. The process of creating a related Work Order has been streamlined using a functionality of Maximo called Workflow. This eliminates additional keystrokes and helps enhance the efficiency of the user. This lesson also provides a review of how to update the Work Order status, and how to determine disposition, if warranted. For more information about this process, please go to Appendix A - Record and Complete Work Business Process to review the flowchart and process narrative. IMPORTANT! If a Work Order has not been created, you will need to create one. Refer to Create a Work Order section in the previous lesson . For true emergencies, e.g. a medical gas leak - the work may be done before a Work Order is created

Refer to Create a Work Order section in the previous lesson . For true emergencies, e.g. a medical gas leak - the work may be done before a Work Order is created. To the right side of the screen, select the New Row button. Figure 7. Actuals Tab - New Row Button IMPORTANT! Labor Section - Labor Row NOTE: Selecting the Close Details icon on the left of the Labor row will hide the details section below it, making it easier to work on recording the required information. Step 6. In the Work Action Code field, select the Select Value then select the appropriate Work Action Code . (magnifying glass) icon and Figure 9. Work Action Code - Select Value Dialog Box Step 7. te, to the right of the Start Date field, select the Calendar icon and then select the appropriate date. Figure 10. Start Date - Calendar IMPORTANT! You cannot record Labor for a future date and time. The amount of Regular Hours recorded cannot exceed the amount of time that has lapsed between the Start Date/Start Time and the current date and time. Step 8. In the Regular Hours field, enter the number of hours you spent to complete the work. For example, to enter one- and one-half hours of labor, enter the decimal value 1.5 or the time value 1:30. If you enter the decimal value 1.5 Maximo will automatically convert it to the time value 1:30. Figure 11. Regular Hours Field Step 9. If appropriate, select the New Row button to record more Labor for yourself. Step 10. Select the Save icon on the toolbar. IMPORTANT! Once a Labor transaction is saved, it is not editable . Step 10. Select the Save icon on the toolbar. IMPORTANT! Once a Labor transaction is saved, it is not editable . If Labor hours need to be adjusted, add a new row, and enter the corrected hours. If Labor hours need to be reduced, add a new row, and enter in a negative number , in the Regular Hours field to correct the hours (example: Enter -.5 hours will result in a reduction of one half hour). Keep in mind: - · 2 hours, thirty minutes can be entered as 2:30 or as 2.5 in the Regular Hours field. - · 2 hours, fifteen minutes can be entered as 2:15 or as 2.25 in the Regular Hours field. ## Record Labor Hours for Someone Else Next, we will look at how on how to record Labor hours for someone else. - Step 1. In this lesson, you will learn how to update a Work Order, reassign the Responsible Department, develop a Job Plan, apply the Job Plan to the related Work Order, and finally assign ownership and approve the Work Order. For more information about this process, please go to Appendix A - Plan and Approve Work Business Process to view the flowchart and narrative for this process; also, please go to Appendix B - Schedule PM Work Business Process to view the flowchart and narrative for that closely related process. ## User Roles and Responsibilities The audience for this training includes the following user roles: | Role | Responsibility | |-------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Job Plans are detailed descriptions of work tasks (operations), labor, materials, and tools for a type of work and allow users to plan and standardize work tasks. We will cover below the three most common status codes. - 1. When should you update Work Order Status to In Progress ? INPRG In Progress or Initiated ( ) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either. However, you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - 2. the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - 2. When should you Defer a Work Order (accomplished by updating the PM Results field to DEFER )? DEFER Deferred ( ) indicates that the PM Work Order cannot be completed. This status requires selection of one of the following options in the Deferred Reason field: - · CNL - Could Not Locate - · IU - In Use - · LO - Loaned Out - · OOS - Out of Service - · OTHER - Other NOTE: If the reason the Work Order was deferred is NOT listed in the options available (listed above), select OTHER in the Deferred Reason field and then type the appropriate reason in the Other Deferral Reason field, which is required before the Work Order can be saved. IMPORTANT! This code is used to track all PM Work Orders that are deferred for reasons other than the options available. ## 3. When should you update Work Order Status to Canceled ? CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled. If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it, you can change the status to WAPPR (Waiting on Approval) then change to CAN. NOTE: No changes can be made to the Work Order once it has been canceled. The following status codes can be used on a Work Order: - · APPR (Approved) indicates the work plan has been approved and the work can begin. You can report actuals against approved Work Orders. Once the status is changed to Approved, the user can no longer delete tasks, labor or materials using the Delete Row (trash can) icon. The user can change the status of individual tasks to Canceled which is similar to deleting a task. The Work Order status can be changed back to Waiting Approval from Approved if other information needs to be modified. However, information cannot be deleted if the Work Order was previously in an Approved status. - · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against

- · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it you can change the status to WAPPR then change to CAN. - · CLOSE (Closed) finalizes and closes the Work Order. No changes can be made to the Work Order. - · COMP (Completed) status indicates all the physical work has been completed . You cannot delete any information on the Work Order when the status is complete, however, information (Log, Labor, Material, etc.) can be added to the Work Order. Once a Work Order has been completed, the only status that it can be changed to is closed. - · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or

- · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either, but you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - · WAPPR (Waiting Approval) is the default status for creating new Work Orders. In this status, a user can delete tasks, labor and materials with ease by using the Delete Row (trash can) icon and saving the record. However, a user cannot update the labor or materials information on the Actuals tab while the status is in Waiting on Approval. If a PM Work Order must be deferred, a PM Result of DEFER is recorded, and a value is added to describe the reason for deferral. Examples of reasons for deferral include: - · Asset could not be located - · Asset is out of service - · Asset is loaned out A deferred Work Order may be continued to completion if a missing Asset is found within the time frame in which the Work Order must be performed.

Otherwise, the Work Order will be closed with a PM result of deferred, with narrative describing the reason. Transactions are logged and digital signatures captured for use in autogenerating documentation, such as form 0751. This lesson covers community and role responsibilities in the Asset Turn In process. For more information about the process, please go to Appendix A - Turn In Asset Business Process to view the flowchart and process narrative. ## User Roles and Responsibilities The audience for this training includes the following user roles: | Role | Responsibility | |------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Evaluation of the work order by the appropriate Supervisory level is required to determine the need for pre-turn in work (e.g., decontamination, uninstallation, data sanitization, Freon removal). These Evaluation Work Orders appear in the Inbox/Assignments portlet of FM Admin, FM Work Order Clerk, and HTM Admin based on the Responsible Department of the Asset. NOTE: Any work order with a Responsible Department of MULTI will appear in the Inbox/Assignments portlet of both FM and HTM. IMPORTANT! Should a Turn In Work Order contain an Asset(s) with open wor

NOTE: Any work order with a Responsible Department of MULTI will appear in the Inbox/Assignments portlet of both FM and HTM. IMPORTANT! Should a Turn In Work Order contain an Asset(s) with open work orders other than the Turn In Work Order, the following message will display. The Asset(s) affected will be listed. Though not required, it is recommended to CLOSE open work orders, other than the Turn In Work Order, if appropriate. An open work order is a work order in any status other than CLOSE. This is also a good time to verify the Asset(s) do not have ACTIVE PMs. If so, they should be changed to INACTIVE. Figure 1. Service Requests can be submitted for yourself or on behalf of another person. Service Requests are reviewed by the function receiving them and turned into Work Orders once approved. You have the option of automatically receiving key status notifications for any Service Request that you create. Common uses for Service Requests are: - · Requesting

You have the option of automatically receiving key status notifications for any Service Request that you create. Common uses for Service Requests are: - · Requesting environmental services (EMS) or (EPS) support to clean a patient room - · Issuing a request to logistics (PPM) to turn in an Asset - · Requesting repairs on plumbing or electrical systems from Facilities Management (FM) - · Reporting malfunctioning biomedical Assets (HTM) NOTE: Individuals creating Service Requests in Maximo are the same individuals who created Work Requests in AEMS/MERS. As you learned in the Service Request Overview module, you can create a new Service Request in Maximo by: - · Selecting the New Service Request link in the Quick Insert portlet on your Start Center . Figure 1. Favorite Applications - New Service Request Link NOTE: You may also select Go To > Self Service>Service Requests>Create Service Request from the Navigation Bar.

All required fields should be filled out before you can submit your Service Request for approval. Attachments ## Evaluate a Service Request The Service Requestor creates a Service Request in Maximo and submits it for approval. - · If the facility has Work Order Clerks who are Maximo users, then they are the first responders to incoming requests. - · If there is no Work Order Clerk at the facility, then the Admin is the first responder to incoming requests. IMPORTANT! EPS Admins will receive an automatic notification when a new Service Request is created for the EPS Responsible Department . The Admin or Work Order Clerk evaluates the Service Request: - · If the Service Request is valid, the Admin, Supervisor, or Work Order Clerk needs to determine whether or not planning is required and then route the workflow in order to generate the Work Order in Maximo. If the Service Request is invalid, the Admin or Work Order Clerk needs to disapprove it, which is what we will learn next. ## Disapprove a Service Request If the Service Request is not valid, the Admin or Work Order Clerk disapproves the Service Request in Maximo, which ends the process. A WORK ORDER ## Create a Related Work Order from a Service Request Work Orders can be created automatically from existing Service Requests. This creates a relationship between the two records and the Asset and/or location from the originating Service Request is copied to the related Work Order. There are various ways to create a Work Order, depending on how it originated: - · If the request came in as a Service Request, then you will create the Work Order from the Service Request, which is the case in our scenario. (This will take place the majority of the time.) - · If the request originated as a Work Order, then you will use the Work Order Tracking application. For example: standing work orders, work orders created for professional services. Refer to Appendix A - Creating a Work Order Using Work Order Tracking for the steps on how to do it. - · If the work being reported has been completed before a Work Order was ever created, you will use the Quick Reporting application.

ork Order Using Work Order Tracking for the steps on how to do it. - · If the work being reported has been completed before a Work Order was ever created, you will use the Quick Reporting application. This is a relatively rare scenario; it is generally reserved for work either, found and fixed while away from your desk or for work that couldn't wait for a work order to be created. Refer to Appendix B: - Creating a Work Order Using Quick Reporting for details related to this process. Note that the preferred method to create a Work Order is using Work Order Tracking and not Quick Reporting. The process of creating a related Work Order has been streamlined using a functionality of Maximo called Workflow. This eliminates additional keystrokes and helps enhance the efficiency of the user. Completed Work Orders Report ## REVIEW AND DETERMINE WORK ORDER DISPOSITION IMPORTANT! The Admin or Work Lead does not review all completed Work Orders. However, if it is determined that a review is required, the Admin or Work Lead will review the Work Order and determine a disposition that can vary by circumstances. Generally, discrepancies are reconciled. Maximo sends a status change notice to the Requestor or on behalf of user, if it was indicated on the Service Request that they wanted status change notifications. If no review is required, Maximo will close a Work Order with a status of Complete after a 365-day period of inactivity.

## ASSESS READINESS This step is completed outside Maximo. Check that you have any parts, tools or consumables required to perform the work, and that you do not need a maintenance contract written for an outside vendor to perform the work. If the Work Order requires parts, change the Work Order status to Waiting on Parts . If the Work Order requires contracting, change the Work Order status to Waiting on Contracting . The Admin or Work Lead then assesses readiness (meaning a required contract or needed parts are ready for use). We will cover below the three most common status codes. - 1. When should you update Work Order Status to In Progress ? INPRG In Progress or Initiated ( ) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor, or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either. However, you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - 2. When should you Defer a Work Order (accomplished by updating the PM Results f

When should you Defer a Work Order (accomplished by updating the PM Results field to DEFER )? DEFER Deferred ( ) indicates that the PM Work Order cannot be completed. This status requires selection of one of the following options in the Deferred Reason field: - · CNL - Could Not Locate - · IU - In Use - · LO - Loaned Out - · OOS - Out of Service - · OTHER - Other NOTE: If the reason the Work Order was deferred is NOT listed in the options available (listed above), select OTHER in the Deferred Reason field and then type the appropriate reason in the Other Deferral Reason field, which is required before the Work Order can be saved. IMPORTANT! This code is used to track all PM Work Orders that are deferred for reasons other than the options available. ## 3. When should you update Work Order Status to Canceled ? ll PM Work Orders that are deferred for reasons other than the options available. ## 3. When should you update Work Order Status to Canceled ? CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled. If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it, you can change the status to WAPPR (Waiting on Approval) then change to CAN. NOTE: No changes can be made to the Work Order once it has been canceled. 2 Plan and Approve Work. | ## APPENDIX B - WORK ORDER STATUS CODES Work Order status may be changed by selecting a Change Status icon on the toolbar. Changing the status also saves the Work Order. The following status codes can be used on a Work Order: - · APPR (Approved) indicates the work plan has been approved and the work can begin. You can report actuals against approved Work Orders. Once the status is changed to Approved, the user can no longer delete tasks, labor or materials using the Delete Row (trash can) icon. The user can change the status of individual tasks to Canceled which is similar to deleting a task. The Work Order status can be changed back to Waiting Approval from Approved if other information needs to be modified. However, information cannot be deleted if the Work Order was previously in an Approved status. - · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against

- · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it you can change the status to WAPPR then change to CAN. - · CLOSE (Closed) finalizes and closes the Work Order. No changes can be made to the Work Order. - · COMP (Completed) status indicates all the physical work has been completed . You cannot delete any information on the Work Order when the status is complete, however, information (Log, Labor, Material, etc.) can be added to the Work Order. Once a Work Order has been completed, the only status that it can be changed to is closed. - · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor, o

- · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor, or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either, but you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - · WAPPR (Waiting Approval) is the default status for creating new Work Orders. In this status, a user can delete tasks, labor, and materials with ease by using the Delete Row (trash can) icon and saving the record. However, a user cannot update the labor or materials information on the Actuals tab while the status is in Waiting on Approval. This is the only status in which a Job Plan can be applied or removed. - · WMATL (Waiting on Material) indicates materials must arrive before the work c

tab while the status is in Waiting on Approval. This is the only status in which a Job Plan can be applied or removed. - · WMATL (Waiting on Material) indicates materials must arrive before the work can be performed. - · WPART (Waiting for Parts) indicates waiting for part before work can be performed or completed. - · WIRSC (Waiting for Internal Resources) indicates waiting for internal VA resources before work can be performed or completed. - · WCONT (Waiting for Contractor) indicates waiting for a contractor before work can be performed or completed. - · WOIT (Waiting for OIT) indicates waiting for OIT before work can be performed or completed. - · WVEND (Waiting for Vendor) indicates waiting for a vendor before work can be performed or completed. - · WPCOND (Waiting on Plant Condition) indicates you don't currently have access to the Asset or location, so the work cannot be performed until you do. If a PM Work Order must be deferred, a PM Result of DEFER is recorded, and a value is added to describe the reason for deferral. Examples of reasons for deferral include: - · Asset could not be located - · Asset is out of service - · Asset is loaned out A deferred Work Order may be continued to completion if a missing Asset is found within the time frame in which the Work Order must be performed.

ed - · Asset is out of service - · Asset is loaned out A deferred Work Order may be continued to completion if a missing Asset is found within the time frame in which the Work Order must be performed. Otherwise, the Work Order will be closed with a PM result of deferred, with narrative describing the reason. For more information about this process, please go to Appendix A - Defer Work Business Process to view the flowchart and process narrative. ## User Roles and Responsibilities The audience for this training includes the following user roles: | Role | Responsibility | |-------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | FMAdmin | Receives, classifies and disposes building service equipment(BSE) Assets; reviewsand approvesWork Orders; creates PMs (preventive maintenance

Routes are used on PMs intended to cover multiple Assets or Locations to facilitate creating multiple PM Work Orders or Work Orders that list multiple Assets. This hierarchy has a parent Work Order for the Asset or location on the PM record. The child records in the hierarchy are for each Asset or location listed on the route.
